## Real-Time Updates from Extension (`handleUserWsMessage`)

`handleUserWsMessage` listens for three WS event types:

| type | action |
|---|---|
| `agent_update` — session **not yet** in `_loadedApps` | Call `loadApplications(true)` to surface a card submitted from another tab (extension); return immediately |
| `agent_update` — session already in `_loadedApps` | Ignore (workflow progress update, no card action needed) |
| `workflow_complete` / `workflow_error` | Mark notified → reload apps → fire `notifyReady` toast |

**Critical ordering:** Do **not** call `_markAnalysisNotified` before `await loadApplications(true)` here — `notifyReady()` performs the mark internally; pre-marking blocked the completion toast. After reload, resolve title/company from `_loadedApps` (may be empty for failed workflows) and pass **`wsFailureDetail`** from `msg.data.error` when `type === 'workflow_error'`. **`notifyReady`** stores dedupe keys as **`c:{session_id}`** (completed) vs **`f:{session_id}`** (failed) in `applypilot_notified_analyses` so a failure toast is never suppressed by an unrelated completion for the same session.

```javascript
async function handleUserWsMessage(msg) {
    const type      = String(msg['type'] || '');
    const sessionId = String(msg['session_id'] || '');
    // ... agent_update branch, then workflow_complete / workflow_error only ...
    await loadApplications(true);
    loadStats();
    const appAfter = _loadedApps.find(a => String(a['workflow_session_id'] || a['id']) === sessionId);
    const jobTitle = appAfter ? String(appAfter['job_title'] || 'Job Application') : 'Job Application';
    const companyName = appAfter ? displayCompanyNameOrUnknown(appAfter['company_name']) : 'Unknown';
    let wsFailureDetail = '';
    if (type === 'workflow_error') {
        const d = msg['data'];
        if (d && typeof d === 'object' && d['error'] != null) wsFailureDetail = String(d['error']);
    }
    notifyReady(jobTitle, companyName, sessionId, type === 'workflow_error', wsFailureDetail);
}
```

## Toast Deduplication — `notifyReady`

`notifyReady(jobTitle, companyName, detailId, failed, failureDetail)` is guarded at its **entry point** to prevent duplicate toasts regardless of which code path calls it (WS handler, poll fallback, or `syncProcessingApps` "came back" path). **`_terminalNotifyKey(sessionId, failed)`** returns **`f:${sessionId}`** when `failed` is true and **`c:${sessionId}`** when false; **`_markAnalysisNotified`** / **`_isAnalysisNotified`** take **`(sessionId, failed)`** and use that key. **Legacy:** a bare **`sessionId`** in the JSON array still means “completion already toasted” for backward compatibility.

```javascript
function _terminalNotifyKey(sessionId, failed) {
    return failed ? `f:${sessionId}` : `c:${sessionId}`;
}

function notifyReady(jobTitle, companyName, detailId, failed, failureDetail) {
    if (detailId && _isAnalysisNotified(detailId, failed)) return;

    _markAnalysisNotified(detailId, failed);  // BEFORE DOM creation

    // ... formatWorkflowFailureDetail, duplicate headline, append .alert.alert-warning / .alert-success ...
}
```

**Never remove this guard** — without it, the WebSocket handler and the `pollProcessingApps` fallback can both fire within the same event-loop turn (the poll's HTTP response arrives while `handleUserWsMessage` is awaiting `loadApplications`), producing two identical toasts.

### Failure copy and actions

- **`formatWorkflowFailureDetail(raw)`** — Shortens noisy Gemini quota / rate-limit strings for the toast; strips legacy **`[agent_name]`** prefixes from stored `error_messages`.
- When **`failed === true`**, the toast has **no** primary/secondary link (failed analyses are not listed; user dismisses with the close control only). Pass **`failureDetail`** from `GET /api/v1/workflow/status/...` `error_messages[0]` or WebSocket `data.error` when available.
- **Duplicate job (server message contains *already have an application for this job*)** — headline **"Duplicate job — not added"** (instead of **"Analysis failed"**); still **`alert-warning`** like other workflow failures (yellow is not “non-failure,” it is the standard style for terminal workflow errors on the dashboard).

## Duplicate workflow start — `RES_3002`

When `POST /api/v1/workflow/start` returns **409** with `error_code === 'RES_3002'`, the user already has a non-deleted application for the same job (URL, title+company, or long-text fingerprint — see `applypilot-core.mdc`).

- **`ui/src/pages/dashboard-new-application.ts`** — show a **warning**-style alert with the API message; optionally set `sessionStorage` keys (`new_application_toast`, `new_application_session_id`) so a post-redirect toast can deep-link to the existing application when `details` include `session_id`.
- Shared API errors attach `errorCode` via **`ui/src/shared/api.ts`** — treat `RES_3002` as a warning, not a red failure banner.

Integration coverage: `tests/test_api/test_workflow.py` (duplicate URL / duplicate manual text).

### Duplicate after analysis starts (not HTTP 409)

If **`POST /workflow/start` did not return `RES_3002`** (e.g. missing URL/title at submit, or fingerprint mismatch), the server can still detect a duplicate **after** the Job Analyzer resolves title+company or when applying the final **`job_applications`** row hits **`uq_user_job_company`**. The run ends as **`workflow_error`** with the same user-facing copy as **`RES_3002`**. The dashboard shows the duplicate headline above; **`applypilot-core.mdc`** documents backend behavior (`utils/application_dedupe.py`, `_update_job_application_with_final_state`).

## "Application submitted!" — `_submittedToastShownForSession`

For `agent_update` when the session is **not** yet in `_loadedApps`, the user WebSocket can emit many events before the card exists. **`ui/src/pages/dashboard-home.ts`** keeps a **`Set`** (`_submittedToastShownForSession`) so **"Application submitted! …"** fires **once per `session_id`**, combined with the **sessionStorage** toast on redirect from the new-application page. **Never remove** `rememberSubmittedToast` / `hasSubmittedToastForSession` without replacing them with an equivalent guard — users will see stacked duplicate toasts.

## Processing Cards — Skeleton Shimmer While Analyzing

`renderCard` shows skeleton shimmer lines instead of empty or placeholder text when `status === 'processing'` and `job_title` / `company_name` are not yet populated:

```javascript
const isProcessing = status === 'processing';
const titleHtml = app['job_title']
    ? `<h6 class="application-title">${escapeHtml(String(app['job_title']))}</h6>`
    : isProcessing
        ? `<div class="skeleton-line skeleton-title" aria-hidden="true"></div>`
        : `<h6 class="application-title">Job Application</h6>`;
const companyHtml = app['company_name'] && !isPlaceholderCompanyName(app['company_name'])
    ? `<div class="company-name">${escapeHtml(String(app['company_name']))}</div>`
    : isProcessing
        ? `<div class="skeleton-line skeleton-subtitle" aria-hidden="true"></div>`
        : `<div class="company-name">Unknown</div>`;
```

The skeleton classes (`.skeleton-line`, `.skeleton-title`, `.skeleton-subtitle`) are defined in `app.css` with a shimmer animation. **Never show "Job Application" / "Company" placeholder text for a processing card** — the skeleton communicates loading state without suggesting incorrect data.

## Unknown employer — `isPlaceholderCompanyName()` / `displayCompanyNameOrUnknown()`

`ui/src/pages/dashboard-home.ts` defines **`isPlaceholderCompanyName(raw)`** (keep in sync with the same helper in **`ui/src/pages/application-detail.ts`** / shared modules) to detect empty values, common text placeholders (`n/a`, `unknown`, …), and **dash-only** strings (ASCII hyphen, en dash, em dash, Unicode minus, optional whitespace).

- **`renderCard`**: show a real `.company-name` line only when `app['company_name']` is present **and** `!isPlaceholderCompanyName(...)`; otherwise use the skeleton (while `processing`) or **`Unknown`**.
- **`displayCompanyNameOrUnknown(raw)`**: use for **`notifyReady`**, **`syncProcessingApps`** polling maps, and **`handleUserWsMessage`** so completion toasts say `… at Unknown`, not `… at —`, when the API stored a punctuation placeholder.

